{ This is a complete repertoire for Black vs. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  based on the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, characterized by the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  , attacking White's e-pawn.  My approach to the opening is to remain in my comfort zone while taking my opponent out of theirs. By playing a rare move on turn 2, you immediately take control of the trajectory of the game and take the opponent out of their usual patterns. No Open Sicilians today! When you put your opponent into unfamiliar scenarios, they often make mistakes. This is borne out by the data: this line scores very well in games between amateur players.  The Nimzowitsch Sicilian also adds the element of provocation: you're inviting White's e-pawn to advance and attack the knight. This makes many opponents feel compelled to try to crush you immediately. But because it's such a rare choice, they usually won't be well prepared. Over-aggression combined with a lack of preparation is a recipe for disaster – for the opponent. And once you finish the course, you'll know how to handle everything they can throw at you.  As a 100 Repertoire, this course is a full repertoire for Black vs. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  . You might have noticed that it's much shorter than many other opening books and courses. Many players still don't believe me when I tell them they don't have to memorize tons of lines to be successful in the opening. But I heard from lots of players of all levels who had success with my previous course, 100 Repertoires: Réti  @@StartBracket@@  1.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@  .  I also put the repertoire to the test myself. I played it in a tournament at the Charlotte Chess Center where I scored 3.5/4 with Black, including wins against WGM Dina Belenkaya and GM Alonso Zapata, and won the tournament. I didn't add any wrinkles – I played the lines exactly as they appear in the course. So I am 100% confident that you can have success with a 100-line repertoire at the club level and even at the master level! }
