1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nf3
{ White develops a knight towards the center. This often signals an intention to play the Open Sicilian by going for the next move, but we have other plans... }
2... Nf6
{ The starting move of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian. Black immediately attacks the pawn on e4 and forces White to react. Of course, this is very provocative because White can advance while attacking the knight. }
3. Nc3
{ White declines to chase our knight, and simply develops their own knight instead. This move is often played when White wants to steer the game back towards a 'normal' path. But of course developing a knight towards the center is quite principled, and the lines can still get sharp, so we need to know what to do here. }
3... d5
{ 'No soup for you!' In line with our overall strategy, we insist on directing the game into unique channels and making our opponent uncomfortable.   3...Nc6  is of course possible, but gives White their wish for a more standard position. }
4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bb5+
{ A natural move, developing the bishop and trying to disrupt us with a check. }
5... Bd7
{ The best way to block the check. It appears to leave the knight on d5 undefended, but the bishop on b5 is also attacked, so it all works out. }
6. Ne5
