[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nc3
{ An annoying move for us because it makes our usual response of  2...Nf6  very unappetizing. }
2... Nc6
{ No problem, let's just develop the other knight. I even considered trying to make  2...Nf6  3.e5  Ng8  work, but spending two moves to go back to the home square is a bridge too far. }
3. f4
{ This move introduces the Grand Prix Attack, a very popular choice at the club level. }
3... e6
{ Getting ready to fight for the center with ...d5. If we can open up the center, White might regret weakening their king with f4. }
4. Nf3 d5 { Continuing with the planned central break. } 5. Bb5
{ White usually goes for this pin. } 5... Ne7
{ Preparing to recapture on c6 with the knight @@StartBracket@@we don't want to allow the doubled c-pawns@@EndBracket@@. }
6. O-O a6 { Forcing the bishop to make up its mind. } 7. Bxc6+
{ There isn't a good square to retreat the bishop to, so White usually goes for the exchange. }
7... Nxc6 8. d3 Be7
{ Black has the bishop pair and a very solid position. White is dreaming of a kingside attack, but as long as we exercise a bit of caution, it shouldn't go anywhere. Meanwhile, we can expand on the queenside at the right moment.   A sample line could go  9.Qe1  O-O  10.Qg3  f5  ,  blocking White's intended f5. This move isn't forced by any means, but it's a nice way to shut down any hope White had of attacking our king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Alapin Variation 2.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. c3
{ The introductory move of the Alapin. White's idea is to create a classical pawn center by supporting the d4 advance with a pawn. The downside is that the knight is deprived of its natural square on c3. }
2... Nf6
{ There are many ways to respond to the Alapin, but as Nimzo Ninjas, our choice is rather easy.   If you like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , you should love it against  2.c3  since it naturally takes advantage of the downside of White's last move, that the knight can't go to c3, by attacking e4. }
3. e5
{ White doesn't have much choice but to advance, as there isn't a great way to defend e4 with a developing move. }
3... Nd5
{ As in the main line of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, we put the knight in the center. There are a lot of move orders and transpositions in the Alapin, but we can deal with most of them by following four simple rules:  Whenever White plays d4, capture with ...cxd4. Develop the knight to its natural square on c6. If White attacks our knight on d5, defend it with ...e6. Challenge White's center with ...d6. }
4. d4
{ I am considering this the main line because it's the most commonly played in amateur games, but White can also start with  4.Nf3  or  4.Bc4  . All of these moves often transpose because White usually ends up playing those same three moves in one order or another. }
4... cxd4 5. cxd4
{ Again, White could vary the move order with  5.Nf3  here @@StartBracket@@our pawn on d4 can't move because it's pinned to the knight@@EndBracket@@, but it's likely to transpose because they're probably going to play cxd4 sooner or later. }
5... Nc6
{ Sticking with the game plan of developing the knight to its natural square. }
6. Nf3 d6
{ We developed the knight and White isn't threatening anything, so we continue the plan by challenging the center with ...d6. }
7. Bc4 e6
{ This is our go-to way of defending the knight on d5. It has the nice benefit of being similar to the main line in the 2.Nf3 & 3.e5 chapter. }
8. O-O Be7
{ Taking on e5 is a little premature. Let's just keep developing and castle. }
9. Qe2 { White gets off the d-file before playing Nc3 to avoid a queen trade. }
9... O-O 10. Nc3 Nxc3
{ If Black is slow and doesn't seek to pose White concrete problems, that will get out of hand soon. To illustrate the dangers in the position given the opponent's schematic attacking plans, let's imagine it is White to play here.   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2npp3/3nP3/2BP4/2N2N2/PP2QPPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Re1  is always a useful move, not necessarily preparing a rook lift on the 3rd rank but aiding more support to the pawn on e5, which will become clear later. Following  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  dxe5  12.dxe5  b6  13.Bd3  Bb7  14.h4  , now  14...Qc7  @@StartBracket@@  14...Bxh4?  is out of the question due to  15.Qe4+-  @@EndBracket@@ is met by @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pbq1bppp/1pn1p3/4P3/7P/2PB1N2/P3QPP1/R1B1R1K1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Ng5±  ,  when White's attack just plays itself @@StartBracket@@here we see the purpose of Re1@@EndBracket@@. Just one extra move makes a big difference. Luckily, it is our turn! }
11. bxc3 dxe5
{ We can also start with  11...Qc7  followed by ...dxe5, but the main point of this setup is revealed in the following variation:  11...b6  12.Bd3  Bb7  13.Qe4  g6  14.Bh6  and here,  the more active d8-square is not available for the rook. }
12. dxe5 Qc7
{ The battle lines are drawn: White's e5-pawn can be used to launch a kingside attack, but in an endgame, the e5 and c3-pawns will be weak. White must try to attack, while with Black we are looking to restrict White's activity, finish development, and ultimately trade into an endgame.  We usually develop the bishop with ...b6 and ...Bb7 @@StartBracket@@more active than ...Bd7@@EndBracket@@. At the right moment, ...Nc6-a5-c4 is a typical maneuver to start applying pressure along the c-file. White usually sets up a queen-bishop battery pointed at h7, which we'll block with ...g6. }
