[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Bc4
{ This move is not regarded as very good theoretically, but it's seen fairly often in amateur games, so it's worth having a plan to deal with. }
2... Nf6 { The Nimzowitsch Sicilian approach works well here. } 3. Nc3
{ 3.e5  d5!  This is an important response to remember. } 3... e6
{ Now our plan is to play ...d5, taking over the center and chasing the bishop away. }
4. d3 d5 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb3
{ 6.Bb5+  Bd7  likewise doesn't cause Black any problems. } 6... Nc6 7. Bg5 Be7
{ Developing and defending d5 tactically. We'll return to this variation in more depth here. }
