[White "1) Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e5"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 3.e5 Nd5 4.d4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nf3
{ White develops a knight towards the center. This often signals an intention to play the Open Sicilian by going for the next move, but we have other plans... }
2... Nf6
{ The starting move of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian. Black immediately attacks the pawn on e4 and forces White to react. Of course, this is very provocative because White can advance while attacking the knight. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. White accepts the challenge, advancing the pawn and hitting the knight. }
3... Nd5
{ The best square for the knight. It is worth mentioning that  3...Ne4  4.d3  would be bad news, as the knight is trapped. }
4. d4
{ White plays in Open Sicilian style, despite having advanced the e-pawn. This is also a popular choice. }
4... cxd4
{ We should definitely take before White can reinforce or advance the pawn. Now White can recapture with the queen or knight, or even play  5.c3  , which transposes to a line we'll cover in the Alapin chapter. }
5. Qxd4
{ White attacks our knight. However, the queen will soon get attacked in turn. }
5... e6 { Protecting the knight and getting ready to develop the bishop. } 6.
Bc4 { Developing the bishop is also a popular choice. } 6... Nc6
{ Developing the knight and gaining a tempo on the queen. } 7. Qe4 d6
{ Compared to the similar position with White's pawn on c4, playing ...f5 does not work as well here. Weakening the king is risky with White having an extra piece out. But this pawn break works well.   7...Nb6  is less precise since after  8.Bb3  d6  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Nc3  O-O  11.Ng5  f5  12.Bxe6+  Kh8  13.Qe2  , Black doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn. Also, bringing more pieces to the kingside with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/1nnbp3/8/4Q3/1BN2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nd7  allows White to develop nagging pressure following  11.Bg5  Nf6  12.Qh4  . }
8. Bxd5 exd5 9. Qxd5 dxe5
{ Black regains the pawn thanks to the attack on the queen. } 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black has a nice endgame with the bishop pair and better control of the center. Having lost castling rights is not a big deal in the endgame, but it's good to know how to secure the king. ...Kc7 might look natural, but could get hit with Nb5+, so it's often better to stabilize the center with ...f6, then take the slightly longer route with the king to f7, where it will be very safe. }
