{ The most principled response. White accepts the challenge, advancing the pawn and hitting the knight. }
3... Nd5
{ The best square for the knight. It is worth mentioning that  3...Ne4  4.d3  would be bad news, as the knight is trapped. }
4. Nc3
{ White continues developing quickly and challenges the knight on d5. From the point of view of 'theory' this is the main move, but depending on who you play against, you may not face it all that often. Opponents without specific preparation often don't go for this move, maybe because they don't want to allow their pawns to be doubled. }
4... e6
{ Supporting the knight and preparing to develop the bishop. This gives White the option to give us an unusual pawn structure with doubled d-pawns if they choose to trade knights.   4...Nxc3  5.dxc3  is possible but risky. White can use the open lines in the center to develop very rapidly. }
5. Ne4
{ Historically, this move has not been very popular, but engines like it, and it does make sense: White targets the weakened d6-square. You may encounter this against very booked-up opponents. }
5... f5
{ Immediately challenging the knight in the center.   5...d6  is also playable.  6.exd6  Bxd6  7.Bb5+  Nc6  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  gives Black doubled, isolated pawns, but this is perhaps not so bad. }
6. Nc3
{ This is the engine's counterintuitive suggestion. It seems strange to spend two tempi moving the knight back and forth, but the point is that with the pawn on f5, Nxd5 is a much bigger threat. The pawn structure with doubled d-pawns is okay for Black with the pawn on f7, but with that pawn on f5, the position would be too loose. }
6... Ne7
{ We answer White's knight tango with one of our own. By moving the knight, we don't give White the option to double our pawns with Nxd5. The engine initially hates this, but Minh Le has played this position against all comers with good results in Titled Tuesday, with multiple wins against Anish Giri, amongst others. }
7. Nb5 { White takes aim at the weak d6-square. Don't allow mate in one! } 7...
Ng8
{ The knight completes its journey back to the starting square! The idea of this retreat is that we are anticipating  8.Nd6+  Bxd6  9.exd6  , when the knight  will pop back out to f6.   7...Ng6  has been played more often, but the knight can get kicked by h4-h5 here. }
8. d4 a6 9. Nd6+ Bxd6 10. exd6 cxd4 11. Qxd4 Nf6
{ A very odd position. White's d6-pawn and control on the dark squares look impressive, but Black's remaining minor pieces have good squares on b7 and c6. }
