[White "1) Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e5"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 3.e5 Nd5 4.Nc3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nf3
{ White develops a knight towards the center. This often signals an intention to play the Open Sicilian by going for the next move, but we have other plans... }
2... Nf6
{ The starting move of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian. Black immediately attacks the pawn on e4 and forces White to react. Of course, this is very provocative because White can advance while attacking the knight. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. White accepts the challenge, advancing the pawn and hitting the knight. }
3... Nd5
{ The best square for the knight. It is worth mentioning that  3...Ne4  4.d3  would be bad news, as the knight is trapped. }
4. Nc3
{ White continues developing quickly and challenges the knight on d5. From the point of view of 'theory' this is the main move, but depending on who you play against, you may not face it all that often. Opponents without specific preparation often don't go for this move, maybe because they don't want to allow their pawns to be doubled. }
4... e6
{ Supporting the knight and preparing to develop the bishop. This gives White the option to give us an unusual pawn structure with doubled d-pawns if they choose to trade knights.   4...Nxc3  5.dxc3  is possible but risky. White can use the open lines in the center to develop very rapidly. }
5. Nxd5 exd5
{ Let's pause for a moment to discuss this unusual pawn structure. The pawn duo on d5 and c5 controls a lot of valuable squares in the center, but the pawn on d5 could be weak since the other d-pawn on d7 blocks the queen from defending it.   Given a move or two, we would rectify that situation with ...d6, exchanging the doubled pawn and opening the queen's path, so if White wants to argue that d5 is a weakness, they need to play d4 right away. }
6. d4
{ White wants to attack the pawn on d5 by opening the d-file.  6.c3  Nc6  7.d4  would transpose to  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3  . }
6... Nc6 { Continuing with natural development. } 7. c3
{ Rather than trying to go after the d5-pawn, White simply reinforces the center. }
7... cxd4
{ Trading first creates the option of giving a check on the a5-e1 diagonal in some lines. }
8. cxd4 d6
{ As usual, we want to challenge White's center and trade off one of our doubled pawns. }
9. Bd3 { 9.Bb5??  Qa5+  would cost White a bishop. } 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Bb4+
{ We take advantage of this check to get ready to castle. } 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.
Qxd2 Bg4 { Pointing out that the queen no longer defends the knight. } 13. O-O
Bxf3 { Giving White doubled pawns and exposing the king. } 14. gxf3 O-O
{ The computer calls this equal, but White's doubled pawns and exposed king look very ugly to me. I'd take Black any day of the week. }
