{ White's only way to defend f2 is to work backwards with this queen check. }
10... Be6 { Answering the check while developing. } 11. Qh4
{ White has succeeded in defending f2, but it cost several moves. } 11... Bxd6
{ Black gets one of the pawns back. This is a good moment to take stock. White is still up a pawn, but Black has compensation in the form of a lead in development. Traditionally, this has been considered one of White's best theoretical lines against the Nimzowitsch Sicilian because White gets to remain a pawn up.  In fact, this was what World Champion Ding Liren went for as White when Minh Le used the Nimzowitsch Sicilian against him. That game ended as a draw, so if you can draw the literal World Champion of chess from this position, I don't think we need to be too worried about it.  However, since this is an important position from a theoretical perspective, let's go through some of White's options, just to feel really confident we understand what's going on. }
12. Be2 { White can develop the bishop here to avoid getting hit with ...Nb4. }
12... Bf5
{ But now we take advantage of the bishop's absence from this diagonal. } 13.
O-O O-O { It's not prudent to grab the c2-pawn before castling. } 14. c3 Rfe8
{ The bishop is a little uncomfortable on e2. } *

