[White "1) Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e5"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 3.e5 Nd5 4.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nf3
{ White develops a knight towards the center. This often signals an intention to play the Open Sicilian by going for the next move, but we have other plans... }
2... Nf6
{ The starting move of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian. Black immediately attacks the pawn on e4 and forces White to react. Of course, this is very provocative because White can advance while attacking the knight. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. White accepts the challenge, advancing the pawn and hitting the knight. }
3... Nd5
{ The best square for the knight. It is worth mentioning that  3...Ne4  4.d3  would be bad news, as the knight is trapped. }
4. Bc4
{ This move develops a piece and creates a threat, so it's no surprise that it's popular in practice. But the bishop can also be vulnerable here. }
4... Nb6
{ Answering the threat to the knight and hitting the bishop in turn. The knight is not particularly well placed on b6, but it's worth it to gain a tempo by attacking the bishop. }
5. Bxf7+
{ This has been tried fairly often in the online database, but it's really less of a sacrifice and more of a blunder, as White does not get enough compensation for the piece.   5.Bb3??  c4  would cost White a bishop! }
5... Kxf7 6. Ng5+ Kg8 7. Qf3 Qe8
{ Defending the mate threat on f7. White's fun is over and they really don't have any attack. Black is ready to take over the game with ...h6, ...Nc6, etc. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e5"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 3.e5 Nd5 4.Bc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nf3
{ White develops a knight towards the center. This often signals an intention to play the Open Sicilian by going for the next move, but we have other plans... }
2... Nf6
{ The starting move of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian. Black immediately attacks the pawn on e4 and forces White to react. Of course, this is very provocative because White can advance while attacking the knight. }
3. e5
{ The most principled response. White accepts the challenge, advancing the pawn and hitting the knight. }
3... Nd5
{ The best square for the knight. It is worth mentioning that  3...Ne4  4.d3  would be bad news, as the knight is trapped. }
4. Bc4
{ This move develops a piece and creates a threat, so it's no surprise that it's popular in practice. But the bishop can also be vulnerable here. }
4... Nb6
{ Answering the threat to the knight and hitting the bishop in turn. The knight is not particularly well placed on b6, but it's worth it to gain a tempo by attacking the bishop. }
5. Be2 { 5.Bb3??  c4  would cost White a bishop! } 5... Nc6
{ Black can increase the pressure on the overextended e5-pawn with ...g6 and ...Bg7. }
6. O-O g6
{ 6...d5  is an interesting alternative, but simply continuing  with the ...g6 plan is fine. }
7. c3 Bg7 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d6
{ Continuing to break down White's center. The natural  9...O-O  is less precise since after  10.Bf4  d6  11.exd6  , Black can no longer  recapture on d6 with the queen. The text move instead gives Black a slightly preferable position. }
10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Be3 O-O
{ This is a situation where the isolated queen's pawn is definitely more of a weakness than a strength. Black has good control of d5, pressure on d4, and can easily finish development. }
