{ The best square for the knight. Often, it will pop out to e6, eyeing the weak d4-square. In contrast, on b6 it would have nowhere to go. White's e5-pawn is separated from its comrades and given the chance we will attack it with ...Nc6, ...g6, ...Bg7, etc. }
5. Nc3
{ Natural development, but White does nothing to address the weakness on e5. }
5... Nc6 { Now if White wants to play d4 it will involve a pawn sacrifice. } 6.
d4 { Arguably sacrificing the pawn is White's best way to go at this point. }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nxe5 8. Bf4 Ng6 9. Bg3 e5
{ We have two central pawns, we might as well use them! } 10. Nf3
{ 10.Nf5?  would run into  10...d5!  , when White is losing on all counts being down a pawn and getting overrun in the center. }
10... d6
{ White has a small lead in development, but Black has an extra pawn and a solid pawn center. Black should focus on finishing development, and White will have a hard time making a dent in the position. }
