{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nf3
{ White develops a knight towards the center. This often signals an intention to play the Open Sicilian by going for the next move, but we have other plans... }
2... Nf6
{ The starting move of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian. Black immediately attacks the pawn on e4 and forces White to react. Of course, this is very provocative because White can advance while attacking the knight. }
3. Nc3
{ White declines to chase our knight, and simply develops their own knight instead. This move is often played when White wants to steer the game back towards a 'normal' path. But of course developing a knight towards the center is quite principled, and the lines can still get sharp, so we need to know what to do here. }
3... d5
{ 'No soup for you!' In line with our overall strategy, we insist on directing the game into unique channels and making our opponent uncomfortable.   3...Nc6  is of course possible, but gives White their wish for a more standard position. }
4. Bb5+ { White tries to throw a wrench in the works with this check. } 4...
Bd7 { This is the most solid way to block, offering a bishop trade. } 5. e5
{ White hits the knight. There are now a lot of pieces hanging and the lines can get confusing, so pay attention! The key idea to orient yourself from a strategic perspective is that both sides want to play e6. If Black manages to get ...e6 in, we'll have a good French structure for two reasons:  We'll likely get to exchange our light-squared bishop, the problem piece in the French. White's knight on c3 is misplaced, preventing them from setting up a pawn chain with c3-d4-e5.  
So White's best bet is to try to play e6 themselves as a pawn sacrifice. If they manage to do this in a spot where we have to capture with the f-pawn, they'll open up our king and slow down our development. }
5... Bxb5
{ First resolving the tension with the bishop.  5...Ng8  6.e6  is uncomfortable to deal with. }
6. Nxb5 Qd7
{ Hitting the knight and also taking control of e6.  6...Nfd7  7.e6  fxe6  8.Ng5  would give White what they want. The knights are creating a lot of annoying threats. }
7. Nd6+ { This looks clever but doesn't actually do much. } 7... exd6 8. exf6
Qe6+ { White doesn't have an easy answer to this check. } 9. Qe2
{ 9.Kf1  Qxf6  would lose castling rights and let Black recapture the pawn. }
9... Nd7
{ Developing and threatening ...Nxf6. Creating doubled isolated pawns with ...gxf6 isn't very appealing. }
10. fxg7 Bxg7
{ Black has a weird pawn structure, but it does control a lot of space in the center and queenside, and our pieces are really active. In an endgame, we can push the queenside pawns. }
*

