a6 { Reintroducing the threat to the knight. } 8. Nc3 Ng8 9. e6
{ This is White's only way to try to stir up trouble. If they don't do it right away, we would play ...e6 ourselves to stabilize the structure. }
9... Qxe6
{ Given that we're headed for a scenario with a pawn up but a weak king, it makes sense to force the queen trade. }
10. Qxe6 fxe6
{ So White got the e6 move in, but they had to trade queens to do it, which makes our king's safety less of an issue. }
11. Ng5 d4
{ The position is still tricky, but Black appears to be holding their own in this endgame. I don't want to force you to memorize a bunch of details in a position you will most likely never face, but let me show you a few sample lines.   12.Nxe6  Kf7!  13.Nd8+  Ke8  14.Ne6  Kf7  could lead to a repetition of moves.   12.Nce4  Nd7  13.Nxe6  Rc8  ,  planning to expel the knight with ...Rc6. }
