[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Closed Sicilian 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nc3
{ An annoying move for us because it makes our usual response of  2...Nf6  very unappetizing. }
2... Nc6
{ No problem, let's just develop the other knight. I even considered trying to make  2...Nf6  3.e5  Ng8  work, but spending two moves to go back to the home square is a bridge too far. }
3. Nf3
{ White suggests that they might be interested in playing an Open Sicilian after all. As Nimzo Ninjas, we can scarcely allow a transposition to an Open Sicilian, which isn't part of our repertoire. For one thing, Black has a lot of control over the center. }
3... e5
{ Preventing d4 once and for all. There's not going to be an Open Sicilian today. The downside of this move is that it leaves a hole on d5, but this line is a favorite of Magnus Carlsen, arguably the greatest positional player of all time, so it's safe to say that Black's position has its upsides. }
4. Bb5
{ This is popular in practice, although to me it looks much more logical to put the bishop on c4 once we've committed to ...e5. }
4... d6
{ Just making sure e5 is defended. The position is similar to the Bc4 lines, but White's bishop is a bit worse placed. We are not afraid of Bxc6, which would just allow us to control d5 with a pawn. }
*

