1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nc3
{ An annoying move for us because it makes our usual response of  2...Nf6  very unappetizing. }
2... Nc6
{ No problem, let's just develop the other knight. I even considered trying to make  2...Nf6  3.e5  Ng8  work, but spending two moves to go back to the home square is a bridge too far. }
3. Nge2
{ Similar to  3.Nf3  , White suggests they're interested in transposing to an Open  Sicilian with d4. }
3... Nd4
{ Physically blocking the d4-square. This move has rarely been played, but when it has been, it scores well, and the engine likes it. What's not to love?   3...e5  does not work as well here,  as White's knight on e2 is closer to the crucial d5-square, as opposed to on f3. }
4. Nxd4 { 4.d3  g6  5.Be3  Bg7  leaves White a bit stuck. } 4... cxd4 5. Ne2 e5
{ Defending the pawn while also controlling the center and preparing to develop the bishop. }
6. c3
{ White tries to undermine the center, but we have a promising pawn sacrifice.  6.d3  d5  , if White doesn't challenge the center, we're just enjoying more space. }
6... d5 { Ignoring the threat to the pawn in favor of quick development. } 7.
cxd4 exd4 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qxd4 dxe4 10. Qxe4+ Be7
{ Black has good compensation for the pawn in the form of quick development. The  rooks are going to come to the central files very quickly. }
