1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. Nc3
{ An annoying move for us because it makes our usual response of  2...Nf6  very unappetizing. }
2... Nc6
{ No problem, let's just develop the other knight. I even considered trying to make  2...Nf6  3.e5  Ng8  work, but spending two moves to go back to the home square is a bridge too far. }
3. Bb5
{ White brings out the bishop, suggesting they want to take the knight and give us doubled pawns. }
3... Nd4
{ Moving the knight to a safe square while also counterattacking the bishop. }
4. Bc4 e6 { Restricting the bishop and envisioning a later ...d5 break. } 5.
Nge2 Nf6 { Just continuing with solid development. } 6. O-O
{ 6.e5  can be met with  6...d5! } 6... a6
{ Continuing to play against the bishop on c4. The threat is ...b5.   6...d5?  7.exd5  exd5  8.Nxd5!  Nxd5  9.Nxd4  cxd4  10.Qh5  is a well-known trap. White gets the piece back with a good position. }
7. a4 { White creates a retreat for the bishop. } 7... d5
{ With ...a6 included, this works. } 8. exd5 exd5 9. Ba2
{ 9.Nxd5  no longer works now that White doesn't  have Bb5+ in some lines. }
9... Bd6
{ Black has good development and control of the center, whereas White's game is a bit cramped. Here's a sample continuation:  10.Nxd4  cxd4  11.Re1+  Be6  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.Bxd5  Bxh2+!  14.Kxh2  Qxd5  . Material is equal, but Black has more mobility, and White's king is a little exposed. }
