{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. d4
{ You might be wondering why the Morra and Alapin are in the same chapter. The answer is that if White goes for the Morra, we can force a transposition to the Alapin. This has two advantages:  It saves us a lot of work since we can just use our anti-Alapin repertoire. In a 100 repertoire, it's important to be economical! It annoys the crap out of the Morra players, who desperately want to sacrifice a pawn and go down in a blaze of glory. }
2... cxd4 3. c3 Nf6
{ This is the key move that forces transposition to the Alapin. Accepting the Morra is of course fine, but it's something else to learn:  3...dxc3  . }
