2. c3
{ The introductory move of the Alapin. White's idea is to create a classical pawn center by supporting the d4 advance with a pawn. The downside is that the knight is deprived of its natural square on c3. }
2... Nf6
{ There are many ways to respond to the Alapin, but as Nimzo Ninjas, our choice is rather easy.   If you like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , you should love it against  2.c3  since it naturally takes advantage of the downside of White's last move, that the knight can't go to c3, by attacking e4. }
3. e5
{ White doesn't have much choice but to advance, as there isn't a great way to defend e4 with a developing move. }
3... Nd5
{ As in the main line of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, we put the knight in the center. There are a lot of move orders and transpositions in the Alapin, but we can deal with most of them by following four simple rules:  Whenever White plays d4, capture with ...cxd4. Develop the knight to its natural square on c6. If White attacks our knight on d5, defend it with ...e6. Challenge White's center with ...d6. }
4. d4
{ I am considering this the main line because it's the most commonly played in amateur games, but White can also start with  4.Nf3  or  4.Bc4  . All of these moves often transpose because White usually ends up playing those same three moves in one order or another. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ This move is legal, but it doesn't make a ton of sense, as the whole point of White's strategy was to recapture on d4 with a pawn, and the queen is going to get hit by a knight here. }
5... e6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Qe4 f5
{ We don't want to let White's queen chill in the center. } 8. exf6
{ 8.Qc2  Qc7  leaves White struggling to  save the e5-pawn. } 8... Nxf6
{ This gives Black easy development and two central pawns vs. none. } 9. Qh4 d5
{ Putting our pawns to work. } 10. Bd3 Bd6 { Simple development. } 11. Bg6+
{ The big point of White's play: we lose castling rights. } 11... Ke7
{ Congrats, you made us move our king. But in the meantime, we've also taken control of the center and developed a bunch of pieces. These factors more than outweigh the king's position. }
12. Bc2 h6
{ Taking g5 away from White's minor pieces. The king can run back to g8 if necessary. At the right moment, we'd like to set our central pawn roller in motion. }
