3. e5
{ White doesn't have much choice but to advance, as there isn't a great way to defend e4 with a developing move. }
3... Nd5
{ As in the main line of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, we put the knight in the center. There are a lot of move orders and transpositions in the Alapin, but we can deal with most of them by following four simple rules:  Whenever White plays d4, capture with ...cxd4. Develop the knight to its natural square on c6. If White attacks our knight on d5, defend it with ...e6. Challenge White's center with ...d6. }
4. d4
{ I am considering this the main line because it's the most commonly played in amateur games, but White can also start with  4.Nf3  or  4.Bc4  . All of these moves often transpose because White usually ends up playing those same three moves in one order or another. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ This move is legal, but it doesn't make a ton of sense, as the whole point of White's strategy was to recapture on d4 with a pawn, and the queen is going to get hit by a knight here. }
5... e6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Qe4 f5
{ We don't want to let White's queen chill in the center. } 8. Qe2
{ This looks awkward, but it's necessary to defend the e5-pawn.  8.Qc2  Qc7  leaves White struggling to save  the e5-pawn. }
8... b5
{ I really like this cheeky move. The idea is to bring the bishop to a6, harassing White's queen. Taking the pawn would be extremely risky, as White's already wasted a lot of time moving the queen around. }
9. g3
{ 9.Qxb5  Qc7  10.Qe2  a5  and ...Ba6 is coming next. Black has great compensation for the pawn. }
9... a5 10. Bg2
{ White is possibly threatening to move the knight and play Bxd5. } 10... Be7
{ It's a good moment to take a timeout and develop the bishop, which also restricts White's knight.   The immediate  10...Ba6  gives White the additional option of  11.Nh4  g6  ,  when Black has to be mindful of pesky sacrifices on f5 if White can follow that up with a check on h5, developing an unpleasant initiative. }
11. O-O Ba6
{ The constant threat of a discovered attack with ...b4 is really annoying for White to deal with. }
