[White "5) Sicilian Sidelines"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. a3
{ With this move, White is usually intending to go for a sort of inverted Wing Gambit with b4 next. }
2... Nf6
{ The Nimzo approach tends to work well when White plays non-developing moves that don't control the center. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. c4 { This is the most commonly played move in practice. } 4... Nc7
{ Remember that this is usually the best retreat when White plays the pawn to c4. The knight often pops out to e6, looking at the weak d4-square. }
5. b4 { White insists on playing in Wing Gambit style. } 5... d6
{ I think this is a fine time to cut off the line. Black has a very solid position, while White is just making weakening pawn moves all over the board.   A good pattern to be aware of is  6.exd6  Qxd6  7.bxc5  Qe5+  , picking up the rook in the corner. }
