[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. b3 Nf6
{ The typical Nimzowitsch move works well here too because Nc3 doesn't combine well with b3, as it would block the intended diagonal for the bishop. }
3. e5
{ 3.Nc3  Nc6  4.Bb2  g6  is fine for Black. White's setup  with Bb2 and Nc3 is a touch awkward. }
3... Nd5 4. Bb2 g6
{ Preparing to put the bishop on g7, pressuring the e5-pawn, and pinning it to the bishop. }
5. e6 { White tries to exploit the long diagonal tactically. } 5... f6
{ Preventing both Bxh8 and exf7+. } 6. exd7+ Bxd7
{ The pawn structure has changed dramatically, but it's landed in a good spot for Black. We can set up a Maroczy Bind-style pawn duo in the center with ...e5, which also restricts White's bishop on b2. Note that fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop is no longer very appealing. Instead, we can look to castle queenside.   For example  7.Nf3  Nc6  8.Bc4  Nb6  9.Qe2  e5  10.O-O  Nxc4  11.Qxc4  Qe7  12.Re1  O-O-O  , with a big edge for Black thanks to better central control. }
