[Black "Wing Gambit 2.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit. White offers a pawn sacrifice to try to increase their control of the center. It's a romantic idea, but not too hard to disarm. }
2... cxb4 3. a3 Nf6
{ Nimzo style! This move is rarely played, but it's actually very logical in this position. Like in the Alapin, ...Nf6 gains strength when White is unable to play Nc3; in this case because we've got a pawn on b4. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. axb4 d6
{ Our plan here is not to grab pawns but to fight for control of the center and the initiative.  5...Nxb4  6.c3  gives White decent compensation for the pawn. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 { Continuing to prioritize  development. } 7. exd6 Qxd6
{ The ...e5 idea doesn't work as well when White can kick our knight with b5. }
8. c3 Bf5
{ The computer thinks this is about equal, but I was taught that the center is more important than the edge of the board. Black is ahead in development and ...Qe6+ could be annoying.   For example  9.Na3  Qe6+  10.Be2  Nf4  would leave White already struggling. }
