1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. d3
{ This could transpose into a King's Indian Attack, which we already covered, but sometimes White tries to play without Nf3. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 d5 { Challenging the center right away. } 4. Be2
{ This is probably White's best try. They get ready to recapture on d1 with the bishop in case Black trades pawns and goes for a queen trade.   4.exd5  Qxd5  is not dangerous, as White's f-pawn is a liability once the e-pawn is traded.   4.e5  Bf5  is a good French for Black with the bishop outside the pawn chain. }
4... e6 { Simply supporting the pawn on d5 and developing. } 5. Nf3 Bd6 6. O-O
Nge7
{ This is a good setup for Black. We're not scared of e5, as the bishop would just drop back to c7.   6...Nf6??  7.e5  is of course something to avoid. }
7. c3 f6
{ We might as well take White's e5-pawn advance off the table. Black is doing well. Next, we can castle, develop the bishop with ...b6 and ...Bb7, and look for the e5-pawn break. }
