1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. c4 { White goes for a sort of Maroczy Bind setup immediately. } 2... Nc6 3.
Nc3 Nf6
{ The plan is to challenge White's central setup with ...e6 and ...d5. } 4. g3
e6 5. Bg2 { It seems that White is in time to control d5, but... } 5... d5
{ Anyway! We are ready to sacrifice a pawn if necessary to blow up White's center. }
6. exd5 { 6.cxd5  exd5  7.exd5  would transpose. } 6... exd5 7. Nxd5
{ White often goes for this to try to avoid doubling their pawns, but it works out in our favor. }
7... Nxd5 8. Bxd5 Bf5
{ This seems more clever than the immediate  8...Nb4  because we remove the option of  9.Be4  .  Now ...Nb4 is a big threat. Black has great compensation for a pawn. We're not afraid of Bxc6+, which would cede total control of the light squares.   Let me show you one funny sample line: @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n5/2pB1b2/2P5/6P1/PP1P1P1P/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne2  Nb4  10.O-O  Bc2  11.Qe1  Nd3  and the queen is trapped. }
