1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. g3
{ White goes for a quick fianchetto. This move order does leave the long diagonal temporarily open though. }
2... d5
{ Trying to take advantage of the exposed position of the rook by breaking in the center immediately. }
3. exd5
{ 3.Bg2  dxe4  4.Bxe4  Nf6  is nice for Black, and White has to lose time moving the bishop around. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3 Bg4
{ Continuing to harass White using the weakened light squares. } 5. Bg2 Qe6+
{ This opportunistic check forces White to lose castling rights. } 6. Kf1 Nc6
7. h3 Bh5 8. d3 Qd7
{ The queen did its job on e6 and can drop back to a safer square. The position is around equal, but I always like when my opponent has a long-term problem with their king position. Next, Black should get the kingside pieces into the game. }
