1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. f4
{ White goes for a Grand Prix setup without first playing Nc3. The downside of this move order is that it allows us to play the central pawn break ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Taking advantage of White not playing Nc3. White's last move weakened the king's position and didn't help develop any pieces, so aggressively breaking open the center is very logical. }
3. exd5
{ White takes the pawn. After this, the pawn on f4 looks quite out of place. }
3... Nf6
{ Aiming to recapture on d5 with the knight. This is preferable to the queen, who would get hit by a knight if it came to d5. }
4. c4
{ White tries to hold onto the pawn. This is very dangerous though because all those pawn moves have loosened their position, and they haven't developed a single piece.   4.Nf3  Nxd5  lets Black regain the pawn in a position where  the f4-pawn is a liability. }
4... e6
{ Opening up the center to expose the weak points in White's position. } 5.
dxe6 Bxe6
{ White won a pawn, but at what cost? Their pawn structure has more holes than Swiss cheese. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to put the bishop on the long diagonal. White's backward pawn on d2 is really not worth much. Black can castle and bring the rooks to the open central files, and honestly, I do not expect most White players to survive for long in this position. }
