1. e4
{ White stakes a claim in the center and opens diagonals for the bishop and queen to enter the game. This is the most popular first move @@StartBracket@@by a large margin at most levels@@EndBracket@@ and a very principled and aggressive one, so any Black repertoire must start here. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense. Black contests the center with a pawn, preventing White from setting up a pawn center with d4, but in contrast with  1...e5  , immediately disrupts the symmetry of the game. For that reason, the Sicilian usually leads to a fighting game. }
2. f4
{ White goes for a Grand Prix setup without first playing Nc3. The downside of this move order is that it allows us to play the central pawn break ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Taking advantage of White not playing Nc3. White's last move weakened the king's position and didn't help develop any pieces, so aggressively breaking open the center is very logical. }
3. e5
{ This leads to a very good version of an Advance French for Black because the light-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@usually the problem piece@@EndBracket@@ can come out easily. }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Bg4
{ Getting the bishop out and pinning the knight. Compared to a normal French, it's not easy to get a pawn on d4. }
5. Be2 e6 6. O-O Nh6
{ Aiming for the juicy f5-square. The following moves are by no means forced, but I just want to show you typical development. }
7. d3 Nf5 8. c3 h5
{ The pawn helps anchor the kingside pieces. There are even some lines where you can force White's king to h1 with a check, then set up a checkmate with ...Ng3+ and ...h4. }
9. Na3 Be7 10. Nc2 Qb6 11. Rb1 O-O-O
{ Black has developed all the pieces to good squares and stands well. One possible continuation is  12.Ne3  c4  13.d4  Nxe3  14.Bxe3  Bf5  , when White cannot save the rook without giving up  the b2-pawn. }
