[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Verner Nielsen − Aron Nimzowitsch, Copenhagen 1928"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ We start with a game from the OG, the man the opening is named after. Nimzowitsch was a highly original chess thinker. Apart from this variation of the Sicilian, he also pioneered the far more famous Nimzo-Indian Defense. He set down many of his ideas in My System, one of the most influential chess books of all time. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4
{ This game was played at a time before engines existed, and opening theory was far less developed. Nimzowitsch's opponent was probably improvising already, but many of your opponents will probably be in the same situation, as the Nimzowitsch Sicilian is still quite obscure. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 e6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Qe4 f5
{ A typical response to Qe4, although it's somewhat less effective when White has already developed the light-squared bishop, giving the queen a natural retreat on e2.   7...d6  was more solid. }
8. Qe2 Bc5 9. O-O O-O 10. a3 Qc7
{ 10...a5  ,  it was perhaps worth taking steps to secure the bishop on c5. }
11. c4 Nde7 12. b4
{ The point of White's play: the bishop is close to being trapped. } 12... Nd4
{ Nimzowitsch was evidently counting on this tactical reply, but it has a flaw.   12...Bd4  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Qe3  Nb3  would have maintained the material balance. }
13. Nxd4
{ After  13.Qb2!  Nxf3+  14.gxf3  ,  the bishop is trapped after all, and Black has to seek dubious compensation. }
13... Bxd4 14. Bb2 Bxb2 15. Qxb2 Ng6 16. Re1 b6 17. Nc3 a6
{ Ruling out Nb5.   After  17...Nxe5!?  18.Nb5  Nxd3  19.Qd4  Qd8  20.Qxd3  Bb7  21.Nd6  ,  the powerful outpost on d6 gives White enough compensation for the pawn. }
18. Nd1 Bb7 19. Qd4 Rad8 { Preparing the ...d6 pawn break. } 20. Qd6
{ White blocks ...d6, but overlooks a tactic. } 20... Qxd6 21. exd6 Bxg2
{ Winning a pawn by means of a fork. } 22. Kxg2 Nf4+ 23. Kf3 Nxd3 24. Re3
{ Possibly White had anticipated all this and thought he was winning the knight, but if so, Nimzowitsch had seen further. }
24... e5 { Another fork trick to save the knight. } 25. Kg2
{ 25.Rxd3  doesn't work in view of  25...e4+  . } 25... Nf4+ 26. Kf1 e4
{ Black emerges a pawn up. Nimzowitsch now uses his kingside pawn majority to decide the game. }
27. f3 exf3 28. Rxf3 Ng6 29. Rc1 Ne5 30. Re3 Ng4 31. Re2 f4 32. Rg2 Nh6
{ It seems a little weird to invest so many moves to get this knight to the edge of the board, but Nimzowitsch is planning to pop back out with ...Nf5. }
33. Rc3 Rc8 34. Nb2 Nf5 35. Rf2 Nxd6 36. Rff3 g5 37. Rcd3 Nf5 38. Rxd7 Ne3+ 39.
Ke1 g4 40. Rf2 g3 41. Rf3 Rce8
{ White resigned. There is no way to stop Black's kingside pawns without losing material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ding Liren − Tuan Minh Le, PRO League Stage Rapid 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a real heavyweight battle. We have Minh Le with Black, the biggest proponent of the Nimzowitsch Sicilian at the grandmaster level. Here he shows he's not afraid to play it against anyone, even Ding Liren, who became the World Champion in 2023. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3
{ Ding is known as a very well prepared player, so it's no surprise that he goes for one of the most theoretical variations. }
4... e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qxd5 d6 9. exd6 Qb6 10. Qe4+ Be6
11. Qh4 { The point of White's play is to defend f2 and remain a pawn up. }
11... Bxd6 12. c3 Be7 13. Qf4 Bc5 14. Ng5
{ Defending f2 and possibly preparing to take on e6.   14.Qh4  Be7  could lead to a draw by repetition. }
14... h6
{ Very interesting. Le forces White to do what he @@StartBracket@@seemingly@@EndBracket@@ wants to do, take on e6.   14...Bd5  is a more solid alternative. }
15. Ne4
{ Ding goes for the more quiet route. But what if he took?   After  15.Nxe6  fxe6  ,  Black is threatening ...Rf8, so White must act quickly.  16.b4  ,  trying to push the bishop away from f2.  16...Nxb4!  Forced. Having sacrificed a pawn and wrecked the pawn structure, Black can't go backwards. This leads to wild complications where Black is down a piece, but White's king gets stuck in the center.   16...Rf8??  17.bxc5+-  ,  counterattacking Black's queen.  17.cxb4  Bd4  and now buckle in for a long computer line.  18.Rb1  Rf8  19.Qe4  Bxf2+  20.Kd1  O-O-O+  21.Bd2  Qd6  22.Qc2+  @@StartBracket@@  22.Rb2  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2kr1r2/pp4p1/3qp2p/8/1P6/8/P1QB1bPP/1R1K1B1R b - - 5 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Kb8  23.Rb3  ,  my computer thinks this is good for White @@StartBracket@@although it's still complicated@@EndBracket@@, so I'm not entirely sure what Le had in mind. }
15... O-O-O 16. Nxc5 Qxc5
{ White has an extra pawn and the bishop pair, but Black is ahead in development. }
17. Be2 g5 18. Qe3 Qf5 19. O-O Rhe8 20. Qg3 Qc2 21. Bf3
{ 21.Bh5  ,  the engine thinks this is White's best try to fight for an advantage. }
21... f5 22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. Be3 f4 24. Qf3 Bd5 25. Qh3+ Be6 26. Qf3 Bd5
{ The players agreed to a draw. This game shows that the Nimzowitsch Sicilian is a tough nut to crack. Ding is one of the best players in the world and seemed to be pretty well prepared, but still ended up acquiescing to a quick draw. }
