[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pavel Martynov − Alexander Rakhmanov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023"]
[Result "*"]

{ Alexander Rakhmanov is another grandmaster who specializes in the Nimzowitsch Sicilian. Here he shows how to take control of the game in a typical structure. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Qe2
{ I've found this is quite a common way for White to react in blitz games. }
6... Nb4 { Pointing out that c2 is slightly awkward to defend. } 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7
8. d3 N8c6 9. O-O Nd4 { A typical idea to gain space and open the c-file. } 10.
Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne4 e6
{ Black's idea is to pressure the c2-pawn along the c-file. } 12. c3
{ White attempts to deal with the backward c-pawn immediately, but this loses a pawn. }
12... dxc3 13. bxc3 Qxd3 14. Qg4
{ 14.Qxd3  Nxd3  lets Black get away with the extra pawn. } 14... h5
{ Continuing to chase the queen around. } 15. Qf4 Nd5 16. Nd6+
{ 16.Qe5  is still not that clear. } 16... Bxd6 17. Qxd6 Rd8
{ Black is up a pawn with a superior minor piece. White's activity is only temporary, the queen will quickly be pushed back. }
18. Qc5 Qxc3 19. Qxa7 O-O
{ Following  19...Qxa1?  20.Qa4+  Rd7  21.Qa8+  Rd8  22.Qa4+  ,  Black would have to allow a draw since moving the king onto a dark square would run into Ba3+ with a discovered attack on the queen. }
20. Bg5 f6 21. Rfc1 Qd3 22. Bh4 Rd7
{ 22...g5  23.Bg3  h4  would have won the bishop:  24.Bc7  Nxc7  25.Rxc7  Qd1+  26.Rxd1  Rxd1  . }
23. Bg3 Kh7 24. Rd1 Qg6 25. h4 Rff7 26. Qb8 Nc3 27. Re1 e5 28. a4 Qd3 29. a5
Ne2+ 30. Kh2 Nxg3 31. fxg3 Rd8 32. Qa7 Rfd7 33. Rad1 Qa6 34. Rxd7 Rxd7 35. Qc5
Rd2 36. Rg1 Qd3 37. Qb4 Qd5
{ Apparently, White lost on time here. The game isn't completely over, but with an extra pawn and more active pieces, Black should be winning. This game shows the power of a plan: Black's idea of ...Rc8 and pressuring the c2-pawn caused White to overreact and allow something even worse. }
