[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Lucian Catalin Carmaciu − Wang Hao, Mamaia 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ Wang Hao goes for a different move order, but we end up in a position from the course. }
3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb5 Ne7 6. exd5 Nxd5
{ As discussed in the course, I much prefer this to the alternative  6...exd5  . In line with the philosophy of the repertoire, we prioritize development and activity, not worrying too much about pawn structure. }
7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. d3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 c4
{ Using the doubled pawn as a battering ram. } 10. Ne5
{ Forcing Black to resolve the pawn tension. In the course, we looked at  10.d4  . }
10... cxd3 11. cxd3 Bd6
{ Correctly recognizing that c6 doesn't need to be defended. } 12. O-O
{ 12.Nxc6  Qc7  would leave White in massive trouble, as c3 will drop as soon as the knight moves. }
12... O-O 13. Kh1 Qc7 14. Qa4 c5 15. Rb1 Bb7
{ The bishop casts a menacing gaze towards White's king. } 16. Bd2 Rab8 17. c4
{ 17.Qxa7??  would run into  17...Bxg2+  . } 17... Bxe5
{ Black cashes in the bishop pair for an extra pawn. } 18. fxe5 Qxe5 19. Qd1
{ 19.Qxa7  would again fail tactically:  19...Qe2!  20.Rg1  Bxg2+  21.Rxg2  Rxb1+  . }
19... Qd6 20. Qe2 e5 21. Be3 Bc6 22. Kg1 Rxb1 23. Rxb1 f5
{ Some players believe that opposite-colored bishops always lead to a draw, but in a middlegame they favor the attack. Wang Hao shows the correct plan of going for an attack on the king. }
24. Bf2 f4 25. Re1 Rf5
{ Perhaps an early resignation, but Black is up a pawn and brewing up a big attack. This game is a great illustration of the power of the bishop pair. }
