[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Aleksandra Goryachkina − Vladimir Kramnik, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game, former World Champion Vladimir Kramnik demonstrates Black's archetypical plan in the Alapin. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ A different move order that will end up transposing to the main line of our Alapin analysis. }
3. c3 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 Nc6 10.
Nc3 dxe5 11. dxe5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. Re1 b6 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. Bg5
{ The wrong minor piece. The bishop can just be ignored here.   15.Ng5  is a better try, forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. After  15...Bxg5  16.Bxg5  Ne7  ,  White has the bishops, but Black can still look forward to playing against the weak pawn on c3. }
15... Rfd8 16. Bc2 h6 17. Bf4
{ 17.Qe4  Bxg5  and there is no mate, as Black's king can run to e7. } 17...
Na5
{ A very typical maneuver, opening the queen's path on the c-file and planning to jump into c4. }
18. Rac1 Qc4 19. Qxc4
{ 19.Qe3  should probably have been tried. Remember, White's chances in the Alapin lie in a kingside attack, so queen trades favor Black. }
19... Nxc4 20. Nd4 Rac8 21. Bb3 Bd5
{ Kramnik is totally dominating the light squares in the center. } 22. h3 Rc5
23. Nc2 Nb2 24. Bxd5 Rcxd5 25. Rb1 Nd3 26. Re4 Nxf4 27. Rxf4 Rxe5
{ Black starts harvesting pawns. } 28. Ra4 Rd7 29. Nd4 Rc5 30. Rb3 Bf6 31. Ra6
g6 32. Rba3 e5 33. Ne2 Rcc7 34. Ng3 Be7 35. Kh2 Bxa3
{ Probably a blunder in time pressure, but White's position was already losing. This shows how positionally risky the Alapin can be for White. If they don't succeed in getting an attack going, the weak pawns become a huge liability in an endgame. }
