[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Claudiu Stanculescu − Mircea Parligras, Sarata Monteoru 2011"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game shows how to dismantle an offbeat opening. White plays for tricks, but Black trumps them with development and control of the center. }
1. e4 c5 2. b4 cxb4 3. a3 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. axb4 d6
{ Prioritizing development and control of the center over grabbing pawns. } 6.
Bb5+ Bd7 7. e6 fxe6 { 7...Bxb5  8.Qh5  would let White get the piece back. } 8.
Bd3 { White has one, rather transparent idea: Qh5 followed by mate. } 8... Qb6
{ Black deals with it by creating an escape square for the king. } 9. Qh5+ Kd8
10. Ne2 g6 11. Qf3
{ 11.Bxg6  Bg7  would win, as both ...Bxa1 and ...hxg6 are threatened. } 11...
Bg7 12. Nbc3 Rf8 13. Qg3 Be5 14. f4 Nxf4 15. Rf1 Nxd3+ 16. Qxd3 Rxf1+ 17. Kxf1
{ The position looks like it came from a Chess960 game, but basically Black is just up two pawns. The king is plenty safe behind the central pawn mass. }
17... Nc6 18. Rb1 Nd4 19. Nxd4 Qxd4 20. Qxd4 Bxd4 21. Ne2 Bf6 22. d3 Ba4
{ White chose to resign since he's already down two pawns and c2 can't be defended. }
